               <desc type="building-data" xml:lang="en">
                  <p source="#bibl000168-1"> The Fogongsi Pagoda (佛宮寺塔) is also known as the
                     Sakyamuni pagoda (Shijiata 釋迦塔) or the Yingxian timber pagoda (应县木塔) and was
                     begun by Emperor Daozong of Liao in the second year of the Qingning reign
                     (1056) at the location of his grandmother’s ancestral home. It is located in
                     Yingxian, northern Shanxi Province, and was placed under the National key
                     cultural relics protection unit. The pagoda is the oldest wooden pagoda still
                     standing in China, resisting a multitude of earthquakes and wars. The pagoda
                     structure stands on a 4 meter tall, 2-tiered stone, octagonal platform. The
                     pagoda has a 10 meter tall steeple, and reaches a total height of 67.31 meters
                     tall, towering above its town today. Created by five octagonal shaped stories
                     in <term ref="/keyword/k000130">diantang style (殿堂)</term>, the pagoda has a
                     mezzanine level every two levels that acts as porch-like timber balconies
                     (pingzuo 平座) (Lin 2016, 121). Each floor is created with two rings of columns
                     connected by beams that create an inner and outer aisle (Lin 2016, 121). With
                     the greatest variety of bracketing in Liao dynasty buildings, the timber pagoda
                     has fifty-four types of bracketing (Steinhardt 1994, 13). Prominent features
                     and artifacts in the pagoda include the Sakyamuni Buddha, the Buddhas of the
                     Four Directions, and the Vairocana and eight attendant Bodhisattvas (Shen 2001,
                     23).</p>
               </desc>
